s Han Chinese and Austronesian Aborigine populations. After World War II, the game was tolerated as a remnant of Japanese culture and then strategically employed by the ruling Chinese Nationalist Party (KMT) Even as it was also enthroned by Taiwanese politicians, cultural producers, and citizens as their national game. In considering baseball’s cultural and historical implications, Morris deftly addresses a number of societal themes crucial to understanding modern Taiwan, the question of Chinese "reunification," and East Asia as a whole.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBaseball playerszTaiwanxHistory. 0aBaseballzTaiwanxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aasia.  aaustronesian aborigines.  abaseball history.  abaseball.  achinese nationalist party.  acolonial era.  acolonialism.  acompetition.  acultural history.  acultural impact.  aeast asia.  aeasy to read.  aengaging.  aethnic history.  agovernment and governing.  ahan chinese.  ahistorical.  ajapanese colonialism.  ajapanese culture.  amodern history.  amodern taiwan.  anational game.  apacific.  apolitical history.  apost war taiwan.  asocial history.  asports history.  asports.  ataiwan.  ataiwanese politics.  ateam sports.  aworld war ii.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026279940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094760340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520947603423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520947603/original  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of C